Some useful command

xdg-open -- opens a file or URL in the user's preferred application

touch -- Update the access and modification times of each FILE to the current time. A FILE argument that does not exist is created empty, unless -c or -h
is supplied.

nano,vim,emacs -- open files (if file does not exist, create the file and then open) with specfic editor tools

permanently alias:
    step 1: open file '~/.bashrc'
    step 2: edit it by appending new alias at the end of the file
    step 3: run '~/.bashrc' by calling '. ~/.bashrc'
    
'.' in terminal: source a shell script (apply the script on the current work environment) see http://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/114300/whats-the-meaning-of-a-dot-before-a-command-in-shell for details.

sudo su: get the root permission WITHIN the terminal (starting at the current directory)
sudo -i: get the root permission WITHIN the terminal (starting at the user's home directory)
